Sometimes Mike would drive him over on weekends too, since they live pretty far from the hospital. Jake would either completely ignore Mike when he showed up or make these Weird territorial comments like when Mike brought Adam some comic books. Jake loudly announced that we already had plenty of books at home. When Mike offered to help with anything we needed, Jake said we were fine and had everything handled. It was embarrassing. Mike definitely noticed because he started keeping his visit shorter. I told Jake to knock it off because his attitude was affecting both boys. Adam could see the tension and Dean started looking uncomfortable whenever Jake was around. Adam finally came home from the hospital about three weeks ago. Everything seemed fine for a few days. The boys were texting constantly and making plans for when Adam felt strong enough to hang out again. Dean even brought over his Nintendo Switch so they could play together while Adam was still recovering. Then last Tuesday, I found Adam crying in his room, not just upset crying, but full on sobbing into his pillow. When I asked what was wrong, he showed me his phone. Dean had sent him a text saying they couldn't be friends anymore and then blocked his number on everything. Adam was devastated and kept asking what he did wrong. I was confused because they'd been fine the day before. Dean had texted Adam about some video they wanted to watch together. I decided to talk to Mike the next day at pickup. But when I went to get in my car that morning, I saw Dean's phone sitting in Jake's cup holder. I Confronted Jake immediately. First, he said Dean must have forgotten it when they visited, but Dean hadn't been over in days. After I kept pushing, Jake finally admitted he took Dean's phone from his backpack when they were at the hospital last week. He used it to send that text to Adam pretending to be Dean. I completely lost it. I started yelling at him right there in the driveway, asking what the hell was wrong with him. He said Mike was getting too close to me and acting inappropriate.

What was the worst part of having a ton of siblings? As the only daughter with eight brothers, I had to cook every meal for 10 people because my mother said cooking was how daughters showed love. My parents had eight boys before they finally got me, so you'd think they'd be excited about finally having a girl. But the day I turned 7, mom handed me an apron and said my real education was starting. While my brothers played video games and threw footballs around, I was standing on a stool stirring boiling pots. My mom would hover behind me listing all the ways I was already while my skin blistered from grease splatters and my back ached from reaching counters too high for a seven year old. By 10, my alarm went off at 4:00am every day because breakfast for 11 people took three hours minimum. When everyone wanted something different. Parker needed eggs over easy but not runny. Josh demanded fresh pancakes, not reheated ones. Ryan wanted bacon crispy. Ben required oatmeal. Isaac only ate French toast cut in triangles. Miles needed everything on separate plates because food couldn't touch. Dylan changed his mind constantly and baby Micah screamed if his bottles weren't the perfect temperature. My feet would go numb from standing on cold kitchen tiles and my arms shook from lifting heavy pans. But sitting down meant starting over because laziness ruined food. According to mom, the cooking never stopped because after breakfast came packing. Nine different lunches with nine different preferences, then preparing snacks for whoever was home, then making lunch for the brothers who'd forgotten their packed ones, then more snacks, then starting the four hour dinner prep, then dessert, then evening snacks, then midnight sandwiches when teenage brothers got hungry. My fingers were permanently stained yellow from peeling endless potatoes and covered in cuts and I'd fallen asleep standing up so many times that I Learned to prop myself against the counter while stirring. By 13, I was missing school constantly because dinner prep started at two PM my grades tanked but nobody cared because what did I need education for? And my whole life would be standing in front of a stove until I died. My growth was stunted from malnutrition because I only got to eat leftovers if there were any. I'd sneak raw vegetables while shopping and consider it dinner while my spine curved from hunching over cutting boards for 16 hours a day. The physical damage accumulated fast because burns that never healed properly turned to scars covering my arms and my hands look like a 40 year old olds from the constant hot water and harsh soaps. I developed chronic back pain that made standing agony and sleeping impossible. When I fainted from exhaustion and dehydration, cracking my head on the counter, mom made me finish dinner with blood dripping into the soup because they needed their meals on time. My brother saw me as kitchen machinery That existed solely to produce food. And they bang on the kitchen door like animals when meals were five minutes late. Josh once grabbed my burnt hand and squeezed until I screamed because his steak was overcooked. And Ryan threw a plate at my head when I forgot his extra, leaving a scar above my eyebrow. They'd eat directly from pots while I was still cooking, burning my arms with their reaching. And not one of them ever said thank you or offered to help or even acknowledged I was human. At 17, I discovered I developed arthritis in my hands from the constant chopping and stirring. And the doctor said I need surgery eventually. But my parents.

My spoiled cousin ruined my prom dress because she deserved to shine more. So I made sure that she would be crowned the prom joke. Bridget and I were both seniors at different schools with proms on the same night. She'd been planning her entrance for months. A custom $3,000 silver gown her mom had imported from Paris. She showed it to everyone multiple times at every family gathering. I bought mine from a consignment shop for $200. It was vintage emerald silk, probably from the 90s, with delicate beadwork. Nothing fancy, but it fit perfectly and made me feel beautiful. That was the problem. Three days before prom, Bridget came over while I was at work. Mom let her in to borrow my calculus notes. When I got home, my dress was laid out on my bed with bright pink nail polish splattered across the bodice, still wet, deliberately poured in long streaks. Bridget's text came an hour later. Oops, was doing my nails on your bed and knocked over the bottle. At least now people will definitely notice my dress more. You understand, right? Can't have two pretty dresses at family photos. She detached a winky face. I took photos. Many photos. Different angles, close UPS of the polish pattern. Then I did something strange. I went to Bridget's house when I knew she was at her spray tan appointment. Her mom let me in. Oh, Lila. Here to see the dress again? The infamous silver gown hung In Bridget's room. Like a trophy. I took photos of it too. The label, the receipt her mom had framed. Yes, framed. The matching shoes, everything. Then I went home and got creative with Photoshop. Bridget had been posting prom prep content for weeks. Nail appointments, hair trials, countless mirror selfies. She had maybe 2,000 followers, mostly kids from various schools who knew her from swim team. I made an anonymous account and posted one simple thing. A side by side on the left, Bridget's actual dress. On the right, a screenshot from a Chinese wholesale website selling the exact same Paris custom gown for seventy nine dollars and ninety nine cents, free shipping included. It wasn't hard to find. The custom designer had just been dropshipping from overseas and marking up 3,000%. But I didn't stop there. I messaged the comparison to Ashley, the biggest gossip at Bridget's school. Thought you should know since she's been calling everyone else's dress cheap. Ashley screenshotted it, sent it to her group chat. Within two hours half of Bridget senior class had seen it. Someone found the wholesale site had reviews. Horrible reviews. Fabric smells like chemicals. Sequence fell off immediately. Nothing like the photo. Bridget didn't know any of this yet. She was too busy posting getting ready videos, talking about her investment piece, and how quality matters more than trends. Prom night arrived. I wore my ruined dress. Yes, really. I'd cut out the damaged bodice and replaced it with A black corset top I already owned. It looked intentional. Edgy even. Like a two piece formal. My date said I looked like I'd stepped out of a fashion mag.

When did you have a valid crash out? When I walked into my 89 year old abuela's apartment last Tuesday, my stomach couldn't handle what I saw. My grandmother was sitting at her kitchen table eating cat food straight from the can with a plastic spoon. She looked up at me with empty eyes, her beautiful silver curls now matted and unbrushed. Mija, you want some? It's too, she said in her thick Spanish accent. I immediately took it from her and told her it wasn't. I checked her fridge to get something else for her. Completely empty, except for three more cans of cat food. Her medication bottles were lined up on the counter, all of them still sealed from last month. My abuela takes pills for her heart and diabetes. Missing them for a month meant she needed to be hospitalized. Her home health aide, Leslie, was supposed to be there. According to the schedule on the wall, she should have been there right now. Four hours a day. Five. Five days a week. That's what her Medicare was paying for. I called the agency. Oh, Leslie just left. The receptionist said she's been there all morning, which was a lie, because I've been there for an hour already. Abuela was wearing the same flower dress I'd seen her in last week, except now it had stains all over the front. Her feet were wrapped in plastic bags held on with rubber bands. Where your shoes, abuela? I Asked Leslie said they were too old. She took them to buy me new ones, she replied. I went to the bathroom to get tissues and nearly gagged. The toilet was clogged and hadn't been flushed in days. The bathtub had a brown ring around it. No toilet paper anywhere. My grandmother, who used to smell like vanilla and clean laundry, hadn't bathed in weeks. The next day I came back early and waited outside in my car. Leslie showed up at 10:00am, stayed for exactly 12 minutes, then left. I followed her to her car and watch to throw my grandmother's mail in the trash, keeping what looks like a credit card statement. She was on Facetime the whole time, laughing about some party. Yeah, the old lady thinks I'm her granddaughter now. It's so easy, she said. I recorded everything on my phone. I went back inside and started going through Abuela's papers. Her bank statements showed ATM withdrawals of $500 every few days. My grandmother doesn't even know what an ATM is. Signature on the withdrawal slips didn't match hers at all. I found receipts in Leslie's name for Louis Vuitton bags, Lululemon clothes, and Coachella VIP passes worth two thousand dollars, all charged to my grandmother's emergency credit card. Then I found the worst part. Leslie had been making my grandmother sign blank papers for insurance. She told her Leslie had put herself as the sole beneficiary of my grandmother's fifty thousand dollar policy. I called Adult Protective Services immediately. They said they'd investigate within 72 hours. I didn't have 72 hours. My grandmother was 80 pounds and eating cat food. I called the agency again and asked to speak to a supervisor. My parents tried to give my inheritance to their favorite daughter. But my grandparents had a surprising twist in store. My dad's voice cut through the kitchen like a blade. We'll be giving your share to Amy. She needs it more. I stared at him. Across the table, papers spread out between us. The will, the numbers, Grandpa's signature. The air smelled of burnt coffee, the overhead light buzzing. You're joking, I said, though I knew he wasn't. He leaned back, arms crossed. Your grandfather didn't understand the situation. If he'd known, he'd have wanted Amy taken care of. You're fine on your own. She's struggling. That's what family does. Mom nodded, eyes wet but not soft. Still be successful without it. Don't be selfish. Selfish? That word lodged in my chest like a nail. It wasn't the first time. It was never the first time. I've been the invisible child, the reliable one, the afterthought. Amy, the golden daughter, got the car at graduation, the dinners for her B+. The audience at every recital. I got silence. Plays forgotten, wins a scholarship announcement drowned under talk of Amy's latest dance costume. Now it was $500,000. And even that they wanted to strip away. I tried reason. Grandpa wrote it down. He wanted it equal. Dad's jaw tightened. And I'm the executor, which means I decide how to interpret his wishes. So it's settled. He crawled up my neck. That's not how Wills work. That's theft. He slammed his fist. On the table. Amy flinched from the couch but didn't speak. Don't you dare accuse me after all we've done for you! Braces, a roof, food! You spit in our faces over money! I almost laughed. Braces, school supplies, the bare minimum twisted into some great debt. My voice cracked, but I held it. You bought Amy a car. You still pay her bills, and now you want my inheritance. Do! Amy shifted uncomfortably, eyes down. When I caught her glance, she whispered, mom and dad know best. My stomach dropped. She wasn't going to save me. So I went to the one person who might. Grandma. She listened, face pale, hands trembling around her teacup. Then she slammed it down so hard

My brother got my fiance pregnant, and my dad gave him the family business and a house. So I decided to make them both pay for their betrayal. I found out on a Tuesday. Sophie called in tears, voice shaking so hard I thought someone had died. She sat in her car outside our house, gripping the steering wheel like she was about to crash it. I'm pregnant, she said. For three seconds, I smiled. We've been talking about kids for months. And she added, it might not be yours. Silence. The air around me turned thick. My throat burned. Who? I asked. But I already knew. Her eyes darted away. It wasn't supposed to. Tell me. It's not Alex. The sound she made wasn't even a word. That was all the answer I needed. I staggered out of the car, knees barely working. She chased me, babbling excuses. Late nights. One mistake. She never meant to hurt me. My ears roared. Three months. Four. She swallowed, nodded. I drove straight to the office. My. My brother was there, smug as ever, wearing new Cologne like a cheap disguise. When he saw my face, he knew. Listen, bro, I can explain. My fist landed before the sentence finished. Blood shot from his nose. The room filled with the metallic smell of it, sharp and sour. Dad and two employees pulled me off. Alex shrieked like a coward. She came on to me. We're in love. Those words echoed in the Walls like poison. Mom pressed her hands to her mouth. Janet, our receptionist for 15 years, grabbed her purse and walked out without a word. That silence said more than anything. Dad raised his hands like a judge calling order. His voice was heavy but calm in that fake way he always used when he thought he was the only adult in the room. We'll handle this like adults. Alex spat blood onto the floor, then grinned through it, teeth red. She's having my baby. You can't ignore that. The room spun. I looked at dad, he looked at Alex, then at me. We'll figure this out. Family is family. I left. A week later, dad called me back home, said he had a

When did you realise the love of your life was actually a sociopath? I was playing truth or dare with my girlfriend, Cora, and now I think I have to call the cops on her. The game started innocent enough with people choosing dares like chugging hot sauce or texting embarrassing things to their parents. As the night went on and more drinks were consumed, the questions got more personal. Sarah asked her boyfriend about his worst breakup. Jacob admitted he cheated on his boyfriend with a professor college. Everyone was getting loose and sharing secrets they'd normally keep hidden. Cora kept giggling and leaning against me, seeming totally relaxed. Then it was Ralph's turn to ask Cora a truth question. He got this mischievous look and asked what the freakiest thing she'd ever done in bed was. Everyone laughed and expected her to say something tame or refuse to answer. But Cora took another sip of her drink and got this proud smile on her face. I took off his rubber without him noticing, she said, pointing at me. The room went quiet for a second. I felt my face get hot as I processed what she just said that had never happened, at least not that I was aware of. We'd always been careful about Protection since neither of us wanted kids yet. I turned to look at her, confused and uncomfortable. What do you mean, I asked, trying to keep my voice light even though my face Was turning. Cora laughed like it was the funniest thing in the world. She was clearly drunk, but not wasted enough to not know what she was saying. The other couples were exchanging awkward glances while Brandon turned the music up a little louder. Everyone could feel the sudden tension in the room. Oh, come on, don't look so serious, Cora said, waving her hand dismissively. It's not a big deal. But it was a big deal. If he'd really done that without telling me, it was a massive violation of trust. We'd specifically talked about being safe and responsible. She knew I wasn't ready to be a father. The fact that she was treating it like a funny party story made me feel sick. Sarah tried to change the subject by asking someone else truth or dare, but I couldn't let it go. I asked Cora when this had supposedly happened. She rolled her eyes and said I was being dramatic. The other couples were getting more uncomfortable by the second. Jacob suggested we take a break from the.

When did being maid of honour become your villain? Origin story. For six months, I planned every detail of my sister's dream wedding. No wedding planner, just me handling everything. Two weeks before the wedding, she refused to invite my fiance of 12 years. People will ask about your wedding instead of focusing on mine. Meanwhile, my brother's girlfriends of two years got invitations. I stopped all wedding work until she apologized and invited him. She did, barely. The ceremony was beautiful. Then at the reception, I found our seats. The kids table by the kitchen, furthest from family. Everyone else was at the VIP table. There's a mistake with the seating, I told her. She looked me dead in the eye. That's where you belong. Her groom overheard and started to object, but she silenced him with one look. He apologized to my parents later, but not to me. She told me not to. My parents were furious. When they found me, my brothers, they walked over to scold me for not giving a speech. You're only a bride once. Stop being selfish. We left and got McDonald's. I posted a photo post wedding meal. My siblings called this an attack on her somehow. Later, my sister explained her seating logic. I didn't plan her wedding perfectly. I look too pretty in my gown and I needed punishment for bringing my fiance. Three months later, I'm planning my destination. Wedding, small ceremony, parents and close friends, only my siblings. Are furious about not being invited. You're being childish, they say. I'm being selective with my money, I reply. Then my sister announces she's pregnant, due in June, our wedding month. Change your date and make me m 0 h, he demands. No. The harassment started immediately. All four siblings calling, texting, leaving voicemails about family obligation. I blocked them all. We had our dream wedding, tiny church ceremony, beach Celebration, five days island hopping in the Philippines with 20 people who actually love us. My siblings called throughout, labeling me a bridezilla for excluding them. My parents understood after what she did, we won't force you to include them. Those five days were perfect. No drama, no criticism, just Celebration with our chosen family. My husband and I paid for everything exactly as we wanted. My parents insisted on hosting a reception when we returned. We'll pay, we'll invite whoever we want, including your siblings. I agreed with one condition. I handled the seating chart. The reception was yesterday. One long table. My husband and I center with our parents, my siblings far end by the restrooms and kitchen. My sister arrived in designer maternity wear, immediately complaining about her seat. This is by the bathroom. There's no mistake, I said, smiling. That's where you belong. Her husband started to speak, but she silenced him. The same look from her wedding. You're seriously this petty, she hissed. You taught me that family sits where they deserve. My brothers tried. Moving closer, but the venue staff, thoroughly briefed, redirected them, assigned seating. Only halfway through lunch, my sister stood to make a toast. Microphone conveniently died. Technical difficulties. She tried shouting over conversations, but gave up. My brother texted, this is childish. I replied, being a bride is stress.

My boyfriend laughed at my gym goals until my trainer made me realise I deserved better. My boyfriend Mateo literally laughed when I told him I'd signed up for a bikini competition. Babe, you realise those girls have been training for years, right? He said, not even looking up from his PlayStation. You can't even do a push up. I just spent $400 on a competition prep coach and meal plans. His first response was to remind me of my weaknesses. I'm starting somewhere, I said, holding the gym bag I just bought. Everyone does, he snorted. Remember when you wanted to learn guitar? The yoga phase, that expensive camera that's collecting dust. This is just another Tuesday for you, Isla. He ordered pizza that night, extra cheese, made a show of eating it in front of me while I measured out my chicken and rice. Want a bite, he asked. Cheese stringing from his mouth. Oh, wait, you're an athlete mode now. His friends thought it was hilarious when he told them over discord. Arlo, my trainer, noticed immediately at our first real session. Rough morning, he asked, seeing my eyes still puffy from crying in my car. My boyfriend thinks this is stupid. I admitted adjusting my new workout gloves. He keeps saying I'm wasting money. Arlo set down the weights he was organizing. You know what I think is stupid? People who tear down someone trying to better themselves. You're here at 5:00am. That's not stupid. That's Dedication. Over the next few weeks, Arlo became my biggest cheerleader. He'd stay after sessions to help me perfect my posing, always maintaining professional distance, but offering endless encouragement. That's it. You're getting stronger every day. When I finally hit my first unassisted pull up, he brought the gym owner over to witness my next one. You gotta see this. EASA couldn't hang for two seconds. When she started, watch, this entire morning crew started clapping. Mateo never asked about my progress, not once. Your boyfriend coming to the competition, Arlo asked one day spotting me on bench press. I almost dropped the bar. He, he has a thing. That day I lied. Arlo helped me rack the weight. Aila, I've trained a lot of people. You know what the successful ones have in common? Support systems, partners who meal prep with them, who celebrate every pound lifted, every inch lost. I thought about Mateo's thing, a gaming tournament he had planned for months. The same day as my first competition. He hadn't even pretended to check if he could reschedule. My ex girlfriend competed. Arlo continued. I was front row at every show. That's what you do when you love some.

My wife smiled at the judge and said, I've documented years of financial abuse. He controls every penny I spend. But her lawyer said, your honor, I need to withdraw from this case immediately. I'm Pete. And six weeks ago, Denise served me divorce papers at our daughter's piano recital. Real classy. She claimed I was financially controlling and emotionally distant, demanding 60% of my plumbing business, the house and primary custody of our daughter Zoe. The thing is, Denise had been acting strange for months. She'd started a life coaching business, acquired her to attend weekend retreats in Sedona, buy thousands in crystals and courses and maintain multiple social media accounts about manifesting wealth. I supported her even when she maxed out three credit cards on business expenses. In court that Tuesday morning in Tulsa, Denise's attorney, Mr Vaughn, was crushing it. He painted me as this controlling husband who questioned every purchase while I apparently lived like a king. Denise had actually coached three of her friends to testify about how broken she seemed. Mister Rodriguez has kept his wife on an allowance, Vaughn announced. Meanwhile, he spent freely on boats and motorcycles. I didn't own boat. The motorcycle was a 1992 Honda I bought for $800 to fix up with Zoe. But Denise's friends nodded along from the gallery like they'd practiced. Here's what Denise didn't know. Five weeks earlier, I got a call from American Express about unusual charges on a card I didn't recognize. Turns Out Denise had opened four credit cards using my Social Security number, racking up $67,000 in debt, buying inventory for an MLM scheme selling Healing Water. But that's not why her lawyer quit. See, I'd hired my own investigator not to follow Denise, figure out where our money was going. He discovered Denise wasn't just in one MLM, she was in seven. Each one promising she'd be a founding Diamond member if she recruited enough people. Her biggest recruit, her divorce lawyer's wife. Vaughn's wife, had invested $30,000 of their retirement savings into Denise's wellness empire, mortgaging their vacation home to buy inventory. Text did von received during court, his wife panicking because the Federal Trade Commission had frozen the MLM's assets that morning for operating as an illegal pyramid scheme. When von pointed at me, he said, Mr Rodriguez's attorney filed the FTC complaint that triggered this morning's raid. My wife is named in the investigation. I cannot continue. The judge called a recess. Denise tried to chase after von, screaming about betrayal and lost investments. Three friends literally ran out of the courtroom when they heard FTC investigation. My attorney then submitted evidence showing Denise had recruited 17 people, including her own mother, into pyramid schemes using our joint assets as proof of success. She'd been showing fake bank statements claiming we were millionaires to convince people to invest. The judge didn't even deliberate. Mrs. Rodriguez, not only are you getting nothing from this divorce, will be liable For all debts incurred through identity theft and fraud, custody goes to Mister Rodriguez. But the cascade was just beginning. The FTC investigation revealed Denise had been using our address as a shipping hub for the MLM products. We had 200.

When my grandfather passed, my cousin presented a fake will saying everything belongs to her. So I exposed her and called the cops. When Grandpa died, the whole family was shattered. He'd been the center of everything. Holidays, birthdays, backyard barbecues. He wasn't rich, but he had a nice house, a good amount of savings, and heirlooms that meant the world to us. We all expected things to be divided fairly. So when my cousin Amanda called a family meeting and said she had Grandpa's will, we all showed up. She stood at the front of her living room like she was hosting a game show, holding a folder with this smug little smile. Grandpa left everything to me, she said. The house, the money, the land, all of it. He trusted me to take care of things. The room went silent. Then chaos. My uncle slammed his hand on the table, my mom started crying, and Amanda just kept repeating, it's legal. There's nothing you can do about it. She laid the will out on the table, and sure enough, it looked official. Stand, signatures, the whole deal. A few relatives even started whispering that maybe Grandpa really had given her everything. Amanda leaned into it, pretending to be gracious. Don't worry. I'll let you visit the house sometimes. And maybe if you're respectful, I'll share a little. The arrogance made my blood boil. But more than that, it didn't make sense. Grandpa was fair to a fault. He Always split things evenly, even when it caused fights. Him giving everything to Amanda? No way. I asked to see the will. She smirked, clearly thinking I just wanted to torture myself with proof. I snapped photos of every page while she wasn't looking too closely. That night, I sat at my desk and compared the signature to old birthday cards Grandpa had written me. That's when I saw it. The signature was too perfect. Smooth lines, no shakiness. Grandpa's hands trembled every time he held a pen. And the notary stamp? It was dated years after the notary's license had expired. The will was a fake. The next day, I went straight to Grandpa's lawyer. The moment he saw the photos, his expression changed. He pulled out a file and showed me the real will. Signed years ago, properly notarized and witnessed. In that will, everything was divided fairly. The house to his kids, the savings split among the grandkids, the keepsakes to specific people. Exactly what we all expected. This, the lawyer said. Holding Amanda's version is forgery and it's a crime. At the next meeting, Amanda came strutting in again with her fake will, acting like she already owned the house we were sitting in. A few family members were starting to cave, saying maybe we should just accept Grandpa's wishes and avoid a fight. Amanda lapped it up, promising she'd take care of everyone. Then the lawyer walked in. He dropped two folders on the table. Amanda's forgery and the real will from his office. He explained everything. The expired notary stamp, the traced signature, even a handwriting expert's analysis confirming the forgery. Amanda's face went pale. This is a mistake, she said.

My entitled brother tattered my hair because I look like a boy. So I turned him from Mister Popular to Mister Loser overnight. My brother Kyle has always thought the world revolves around him. He's 17, the golden child, and my parents practically treat him like royalty. If there's one slice of cake left, it's Kyle's. If chores need to be divided, Kyle gets exempted because he has basketball practice. When I 15 years old, I asked for new shoes and I was told to wait until Christmas. Kyle, on the other hand, gets brand new sneakers every season because he needs them for the team. But the worst part? He believes his opinions are facts. He'll say things like, girls shouldn't wear hoodies, it makes them look sloppy, or, short hair is for boys, long hair is for real girls. He says it with so much confidence that my parents just nod along instead of shutting him down. I've always liked my hair short. It's easy to wash, easy to style, and I feel like myself with it. My friends say it suits me. Kyle, however, hated it. From the moment I chopped it to my shoulders last year, he constantly nagged me. You look like a boy. No guy is ever gonna like you like that. Maybe you should try wearing a dress so people don't confuse you. I usually ignored him, but one Saturday morning, he crossed the line. I was sitting in the living room scrolling Through my phone. When Kyle came up behind me, he had Scissors in his hand. My mom's sewing Scissors, to be exact. Before I even realized what he was doing, he grabbed a fistful of my hair and snipped. I froze. The sound of the blade slicing through was sharp and final. A chunk of my hair slid down onto the couch. What the hell, Kyle? I screamed, jumping up. He laughed. Laughed? Relax. You already look like a boy. So what's a little trim? Consider it an improvement. I wanted to cry. But more than that, I wanted revenge. Kyle was Mister Popular at school. Everyone adored him. When did being maid of honour become your villain origin story? For six months, I planned every detail of my sister's dream wedding. No wedding planner, just me handling everything. Two weeks before the wedding, she refused to invite my fiance of 12 years. People will ask about your wedding instead of focusing on mine. Meanwhile, my brother's girlfriends of two years got invitations. I stopped all wedding work until she apologized and invited him. She did? Barely. The ceremony was beautiful. Then at the reception, I found our seats. The kids table by the kitchen, furthest from family. Everyone else was at the V I P. Table. There's a mistake with the seating, I told. She looked me dead in the eye. That's where you belong. Her groom overheard and started to object. But she silenced him with one look. He apologized to my parents later, but not to me. She told me not to. My parents were furious when they found me. My brothers, they walked over to scold me for not giving a speech. You're only a bride once. Stop being selfish. We left and got McDonald's. I posted a photo post wedding meal. My siblings called this an attack on her somehow. Later, my sister explained her seating logic. I didn't plan her wedding perfectly. I look too pretty in my gown. And I needed punishment for bringing my fiance. Three months later, I'm planning my destination wedding. Small ceremony, parents and close friends. Only my Siblings are furious about not being invited. You're being childish, they say. I'm being selective with my money, I reply. Then my sister announces she's pregnant. Due in June, our wedding month. Change your date and make me M O H, she demands. No! The harassment started immediately. All four siblings calling, texting, leaving voicemails about family obligation. I blocked them all. We had our dream wedding. Tiny church ceremony, beach Celebration. Five days island hopping in the Philippines with 20 people who actually love us. My siblings called throughout, labeling me a bridezilla for excluding them. My parents understood after what she did. We won't force you to include them, though. Five days were perfect. No drama, no criticism. Just Celebration with our chosen family. My husband and I paid for everything exactly as we wanted. My parents insisted on hosting a reception when we returned. We'll pay. We'll invite whoever we want, including your siblings. I agreed, with one condition. I handled the seating chart. The reception was yesterday. One long table.

I got excluded from Christmas for being a plumber. I cut off my sister's law school money. Now she's begging for forgiveness and I'm better off without her. I run a plumbing company, nothing fancy, but it pays well. I fix problems, cover my bills and earn more than people think. Still, my family looks down on me. My sister, Amanda, law school and I've been footing the Bill, tuition, laptop, textbooks. Every time she asked, I paid. I thought that's what family meant. A week before Christmas, my mom called. She never calls unless she wants something. But this time she told me straight, don't come to Christmas. I thought I misheard what, why? She mumbled about keeping things comfortable and professional looks. I rest her, but she wouldn't say more. Later, my cousin Sarah spilled the truth. Amanda told my parents it would look bad to have me at Christmas. She was scared her doctor boyfriend, Craig, would judge her if he met me. The plumber brother let that sink in. I was too embarrassing to sit at the same table, the same sister who needed me to pay her law school bills. The signs were there all along. She never invited me to her school events, never introduced me to Craig. She always told me to just transfer money instead of going shopping with her. She didn't want to be seen with me. And my parents, they agreed with her. They thought it was fine to leave. Me out that night, I lay awake boiling. Not the loud screaming kind of anger, the cold kind, the kind that makes you think clearly, if I was too embarrassing for Christmas, then my money was too embarrassing for tuition. Two weeks later, the spring Bill was due, $21,500. Usually, Amanda would remind me 10 times. This time she just assumed I'd pay. I called her. She answered sharp, like I was interrupting. What's up? Oh, just checking. I said your tuitions do soon, right? Her voice flipped sweet. Yes. Thank you for remembering. You'll cover it, right? I took a breath. Funny thing I heard you told mom I shouldn't come to Christmas. Something about me being a plumber and Craigslist family thinking less of you. Dead silence. Finally, she stammered. That's not.

Did you find out your parents wanted you to die? The grocery store security footage showed my face hitting the floor. Blood pooled around my head where I cracked it on the tile. When I woke up in the hospital, I immediately threw up blood. You're literally starving to death, the doctor told me. I tried to sit up, but the room spun violently. I need to get back to work. Rent is due tomorrow. She pushed me back down. You're 16 years old and you weigh 80 pounds. Can't be right. When did you last eat a meal? Three days ago, I think. She looked horrified. Where are your parents right now? In the basement, playing their online game, like always. They don't know you're dying? They told me not to bother them unless someone is dead. You almost were dead. Almost doesn't count according to them. She glanced at my chart. You work two jobs and go to school. I work at four in the morning delivering newspapers. Then I go to school, then I work at the grocery store until midnight. That's physically impossible. Red Bull and gas station pills make it possible. You're taking stimulant. I have to pay rent or we get evicted. Your parents don't have jobs? They quit two years ago to become professional gamers. Are they making money from gaming? I laughed. They've made exactly zero dollars. But they keep saying fame is coming any day now. How much sleep are you getting? My thoughts kept slipping away like water through my fingers. Three hours on a good night, but usually less. Do you ever feel dizzy or confused? Every single day. But I can push through it. She stared at me in disbelief. Your parents make you work while they stay home gaming all day? They're trying to build their streaming career. They need my support. She examined my arms, which looked like twigs. Your 40 pounds underweight because you're feeding them instead of yourself. You don't understand. They should be able to follow their dreams after the sacrifices they made for me. My manager, Jimmy, had been sitting in the corner listening. He finally spoke up, looking sick with guilt. I should have said something sooner. This kid has been falling apart for months. He has been seeing things at work that aren't real. The doctor turned to him quickly. What kind of things? Yesterday he was having full conversations with nobody for 20 minutes straight. I felt my face get hot. Sometimes when I'm really tired, I see shadows.

What happened when your girlfriend said she needed space? Lucy chose my birthday dinner to tell me she needed space. We were at the restaurant I booked two months ago, and I was literally holding the gift I'd gotten her when she dropped this bomb on me. I need to find myself. You're always texting and calling me. I can't breathe. I felt my stomach drop. What was she talking about? I need to be alone to figure out who I am, she continued. She kept glancing at something under the table and smiling. Brad thinks. I mean, my friend thinks time apart helps people grow, she said. My heart started racing when she said Brad. She caught herself, but kept talking like nothing happened. I need you to stop contacting me. Complete. She was already standing to leave while my birthday cake sat untouched between us. How long? I asked. However long it takes, she said. I looked at her standing there, ready to abandon me on my birthday. Okay. Take all the distance you need, I said. Her face changed completely. She'd expected me to beg. Really? Just like that? She asked you said you need it. She left so fast, she forgot butter jacket. That night, Lucy sent me 12 messages. I watched each one pop up, getting more desperate. I miss you, but this is healthy. The first said, please just say something. Read the last. I turned off red receipts and went to bed. She Wanted to be alone, so that's what she got. The next morning, Amy, our mutual friend, called me. Lucy's having a panic attack. She thinks you're dead or something, Amy said. I almost laughed at the irony. She asked to find herself. I'm helping, I explained, by ignoring her. Amy sounded confused. By giving her exactly what she requested. There was a long pause before Amy spoke again. She didn't mean it like that, Amy said. Then she should have said what she meant, I replied. Amy couldn't argue with Lucy's own words. Lucy showed up at my work during lunch, and my co workers watched her march up to my desk. We need to talk, she announced loudly. I kept typing and didn't look up. I'm at work. You're on your journey, I said calmly. Stop saying that, she yelled. People were definitely staring now, and I felt embarrassed for her. You're embarrassing yourself. I'm just respecting boundaries, I said. Security walked over and asked if there was a problem. She stormed out, humiliated, and I actually felt bad for a second until I remembered Brad's name. That weekend, she came to my apartment drunk at two in the morning. I made the big

What's your I came looking for copper but found gold moment? I was desperately hunting for a cheap apartment after my roommate bailed on me last minute. Had exactly three weeks to find something under $800 or I'd be sleeping in my car. The panic was real. I'd already calculated how many meals I could skip to scrape together a security deposit, and the math wasn't pretty. Scrolled through dozens of sketch she Craiglist post for hours every night. My laptop screen burning my eyes as I refreshed. Obsessively visited places with holes in walls and mysterious stains that landlords carefully described as character. One place had a bathroom door that didn't close. Another had windows painted shut and a lingering smell I couldn't identify. My standards dropped daily. First week, I wanted hardwood floors and natural light. Second week, I just wanted functional plumbing. Third week, I was ready to negotiate on the plumbing. Was getting pretty defeated when I saw this listing. $750 needs some work, which usually means uninhabitable. But at this point, uninhabitable was looking pretty habitable to me. The address was in this rundown neighborhood on the outskirts where street lights were more suggestions than actual illumination. Almost didn't go, but desperation wins over common sense every time. Pulled up to what looked like an abandoned house. Peeling paint hung off the siding like sunburned skin. The yard was so overgrown, it looked like nature was actively trying to reclaim the property. And a broken Fence leaned at impossible angles. Perfect. Exactly what my life needed right then. Knocked on the door, half expecting no answer. But footsteps shuffled inside, and this elderly woman answered. Had to be 80, wearing a faded floral dress. Her white hair was pinned back neatly, and despite the house's exterior, she looked dignified.

Has someone ever made you choose between your life and everyone else's? My teacher made us all have assigned seating and I got stuck in the back next to the quiet kid. He always weirded me out. Never talked to anyone. Just drew these weird, dark sketches in his notebook during lectures. But that Tuesday morning started normal. I was trying to stay awake when a piece of paper slid onto my desk from his direction. Note was folded into a tight square and when I opened it, his handwriting was surprisingly neat. Enjoy your last few minutes alive. My first thought was that this was some weird prank. Maybe he was finally trying to make friends in the most awkward way possible. So I turned back to give him a confused look, but his face was serious. Another note hit my desk, just one word, look. I glanced back and saw his backpack partially open, something dark and metallic visible inside. It was a handgun. My hands started shaking so bad I dropped my pencil. Our teacher was writing formulas and had no idea what was going on. 28 other students in the room. My mind raced through the options. I could run out the door right now, save myself, but everyone else would be at risk. I could yell at everyone to run, but his hand was already halfway in his bag and I'd probably be first. I could pull the fire alarm, but it was across the Room. My stomach churned and I genuinely thought I might throw up right there on my desk. Then it hit me, the bathroom pass. I, it asked to go to the bathroom, walk past it to the office, warn them quietly. They could call the police, lock down the school, do it properly. My throat felt like sandpaper when I raised my hand, Mister Peterson, can I use the bathroom? He barely looked up, just nodded and pointed to the pass by the door. I stood up, my legs feeling like jelly, trying to look normal, casual, like I wasn't about to potentially let 29 people die or get myself killed trying to save them. I grabbed the wooden bathroom pass, my hands sweating so much it almost slipped. As I reached the door, I heard another voice. Hey, can I go, too? I turned around and it was him. My heart stopped. Just wait until he gets back. But he was already standing up. It's an emergency. Sadly, something in his voice made our teacher wave him through. I was walking as fast as I could, but he was right behind me in the hallway, his footsteps matching mine, his hand still in his pocket. The bathroom was 10 feet ahead on the left. The office was another 30 feet. Asked it on the right. If I walked past the bathroom, he'd know. If I went into the bathroom, everyone would die. The hallway seemed to stretch forever. Those Ugly green lockers on both sides, the fluorescent lights humming overhead, a water fountain dripping somewhere. I could feel his presence behind me like a shadow, hear his breathing steady and calm, while mine came in short gasps. Five feet from the bathroom door, 4 feet, 3 feet. My body was screaming at me to just go in, be safe, let someone else deal with this. Then I made my choice. I walked past it. His footsteps stopped for a second and I knew he knew. I turned the corner and broke into a sprint. My sneak.

Exposed. There was this girl, Madison, at our school who made it her mission to be not like other girls. She constantly put down other girls to make herself look better around guys. He'd walk up to groups and say things like, ugh, why are you girls always talking about makeup? I'd rather discuss philosophy or sports. Then she'd flip her hair and wait for guys to notice how different and cool she was. Madison would post these cringe captions like just a girl who prefers books over boys and hiking over heels while literally only hanging out with guys and constantly seeking their validation. The worst part was how she'd trash other girls behind their backs. She tell guys things like, Jessica is so fake with all that makeup or Sarah is just another basic girl who only cares about shopping. But she always said it with this sweet, concerned voice like she was just being honest. This went on for two years. Madison had convinced half the guys in our grade that she was this rare, authentic girl who wasn't shallow like everyone else. Then we had this big group project where we had to present our dream careers. Madison got up there talking about how she wanted to be a marine biologist because she was passionate about saving the oceans and not materialistic like other girls. Right after her presentation, our teacher pulled up Madison's public social media on the projector to show an example of professional Online presence, her entire feed was designer clothes, makeup halls, shopping sprees and thirst trap selfies with captions like retail therapy hits different and makeup is my art. There were literally zero posts about marine biology, the environment or anything she claimed to care about. The guys she'd been trying to impress just started laughing. One of them said, so much for not being materialistic. Madison's whole I'm different persona crumbled in 30 seconds.

My girlfriend's mom asked why we weren't engaged yet. She said, I'm not ready to close doors. What if someone better comes along? I was coming upstairs with groceries and heard everything. I left the groceries and her house key on the counter. Someone better did come along. Her sister Rachel and I had been together for three years. We were serious, spending most nights together, had keys to each other's places, met both families. I was planning to propose in the spring. That December, we were staying at her mom's house for her birthday weekend. Rachel had forgotten ingredients for dinner, so I volunteered to drive to the store. I spent 40 minutes getting everything, plus flowers for her mom's birthday. Their house had a split level entry where you come in through the garage and go up steps into the kitchen. I had just opened the door with four bags of groceries when I heard her mom's voice. When is Matt going to propose? You two have been together forever. I paused on the steps, curious about Rachel's answer. Mom, seriously, not this again. Rachel replied, what? You're not getting any younger. He's a good man. Stable job, treats you well. Yeah, Matt's great. But then came the words that shattered everything. I'm not ready to close doors, you know, what if someone better comes along? That's a good guy, but I don't know if he's my forever guy. I froze. Three bags suddenly feeling like they weighed 1,000 pounds. I'm not saying he's a backup. I'm just. I don't know. He's safe, dependable. But sometimes I wonder if there's more excitement out there. I quietly set the grocery bags on the kitchen counter, along with the flowers with the Happy Birthday card still attached. And I placed my key to Rachel's apartment right next to the groceries. I turned around, went back to my car, and drove to a hotel 20 minutes away. Didn't say a word. My phone exploded 20 minutes later. Where are you? Did you just drop the groceries and leave? What's going on? I texted back once I heard what you said to your mom. We're done. I'll get my things when you're at work. Then I muted her note.

First date, he asked about my hobbies instead of my cases. Didn't mention his yacht or try to impress me with legal war stories. Just listened. I broke my rule and slept with him that night. Patrick was perfect. Cleaned my apartment on his days off, walked my dog, brought my mother 100 roses. When they met, said he worked cyber security after his m I t. Computer science degree, made money in crypto. His phone constantly pinged with trading notifications. All things didn't add up. His work hours changed weekly. Never drove those luxury cars from his profile, never wore those expensive watches. Suggested Olive Garden when my usual place was booked. I appreciate fine dining. I mentioned once foods, food, he'd say, studying the menu like it mattered. I ignored it all because when I mentioned a tough case, he'd massage my shoulders exactly where they hurt. When I worked late, he'd have dinner waiting. When I doubted myself, he'd list every reason I was brilliant. Seven months in, I decided to grab Taco Bell after a deposition. Ran late. Hadn't eaten fast food in years, but Nothing else was open. Walked in and froze. Patrick stood behind the counter in a uniform, name tag and all our eyes met. His face went white. Can I help you? He asked, voice cracking. What are you doing here? I work here since when? Since before we met. The m I t degree, the cyber security job, the crypto fortune, all lies. He was a Taco Bell employee who'd borrowed a friend's car for profile photos, used old pictures from when he'd tried modelling, created an entire fake life. Why was all I managed? You wouldn't have dated me. He was right. I wouldn't have. I need to go.

But when she held it up to the light, it was obviously cubic zirconia from the way it sparkled. Wrong. Her husband admitted he couldn't afford an upgrade, so she bought it herself. And when people realised it was fake, she screamed that at least it was bigger than mine. She pulled out a portable diamond tester to prove mine was fake, too. But when it confirmed mine was real, she threw it at the wall and said the machine was broken. She decided to steal my ring by staging an elaborate heist at my apartment. She hired actors from Craigslist to pretend to be maintenance workers while she snuck in through the bathroom window. But she got stuck halfway through. She dangled there for two hours trying to wiggle free. And when she finally.

I made a kid's Halloween by recognizing him. A few years ago, my boyfriend and I were handing out candy on Halloween when we started running low. He quickly left to grab more. And just a few minutes after he called me, he told me to watch out for this little boy with a train costume. He's not Thomas the Tank Engine. He's Oliver. And he's been upset all night because everyone keeps calling him Thomas. Kid had been crying to his dad that nobody recognized who he really was. A little while later, this boy showed up at the door and his costume was absolutely next level. It wasn't just a cardboard box painted like a train. It was the full train with the kids standing right in the middle and even a chimney where you could drop the candy in. His dad stood behind him recording on his phone, looking tired but hopeful. I opened the door and practically shouted, oh, my god, Oliver the tank engine. I love Oliver. He's my favorite. The change in the boy's face was instant. His eyes lit up and he was grinning from ear to ear. He turned to his dad who looked like he couldn't believe it either. Boy kept bouncing, saying, she knew, she knew I was Oliver. His dad, overwhelmed, just smiled and nodded, still filming the whole thing. As they walked away, I heard the kid repeating, she knew I was Oliver. She knew all the way. Down the street, it hit me so hard, I closed the door and burst.

At the family party, I found my daughter's head shaved. My sister laughed. It's just a joke. I slapped her and walked out while my mom screamed at me. But the next morning she was at my door begging. We attend the annual family gathering every year at my mother's house. This time halfway through dinner, I realized my eight year old Aurora had been missing too long. I found her sobbing in the upstairs bathroom. Her beautiful blonde hair completely shaved off, patches of stubble where the clippers had missed. My sister Brianna stood there filming on her phone laughing. It's just a joke. Brianna's always been jealous growing up. She cut holes in my prom dress, spilled wine on my wedding dress. Mom always dismissed it as just playing around. But this crossed every line. She needed to learn not to be so vain, Brianna said. Luke and Aria held her still while I gave her a makeover. She showed me the video. Aurora struggling while my nephew and niece pinned her arms, crying and begging them to stop. As Brianna and clippers over her head laughing. Other adults gathered in the hallway. Some looked shocked, others struggled to hide smiles. My mother appeared. What's going on? Dinner is getting cold. Look what your daughter did, I said, turning my sobbing child toward her. Mom barely glanced. It's not stylish, but it'll grow back. They held her down against her will. She's traumatized. Posted the video to the Family chat. Brianna announced it's hilarious. Maybe now people will notice something about her besides her hair. I saw the pure jealousy in my sister's eyes, the same look she'd given me our entire childhood. I stood slowly carrying Aurora toward the stairs. Where do you think you're going? Brianna called. Don't be such a killjoy. You're overreacting, mom said. Brianna didn't mean any harm. I stopped. A prank is a whoopee cushion. This was assault. Brianna sauntered down, still recording. I lunged for the phone, but she danced backward. Can't take a joke. That's when I slapped my sister hard across the face, knocking the phone from her hand. The room went silent. If you ever come near my daughter again, I will press charges for assault on a minor. I deleted the video from her phone. You can't delete it.
